               <msContents>
                  <msItem class="#miscellanea" n="1" xml:id="MS_Bodl_487-item1">
                     <title key="work_11314" type="desc">Common-place book of <persName key="person_697" role="scr fmo">John Curteys</persName> of Winchester College and New College, Oxford</title>
                     <note>The collector and chief writer was apparently John Curteys, for the writer was born Nov. 12, 1457; entered Winchester College Apr. 23, 1469; entered New College, Oxford, June 29, 1474 (see fol. 121v); and was apparently a Fellow of New College and of Winchester: Curteys died in 1509. A full list of contents is printed in the Old Catalogue of 1697, see also foll. 1 and (in alphabetical order) iii-v, in the present manuscript. Among the more important items are:</note>
                     <msItem class="#topographica">
                        <note>(fol. vi, 3, 36). Notes about <placeName key="place_7002445">England</placeName>, e.g. church revenues, numbers of churches, shires, etc.</note>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem class="#historica">
                        <locus>(fols. 2, 106, cf. 79v)</locus>
                        <note> Short Latin <title key="work_10957" type="desc">chronicles of England</title>, 1422–1509, ('Opinio vulgaris') and 1066–1447</note>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem class="#historica">
                        <locus>(fol. 3v, cf. 11v)</locus>
                        <note>A short general Latin chronicle, with some special references to Dominicans, to 1286, partly ('Aetates mundi') 'ex tabula Cronicarum <orgName key="org_128973719">cathedrali <sic>ecclesia</sic> Lincolnie</orgName>', and at fol. 6 a note on Friday</note>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem class="#versus #proverbia">
                        <locus>(fols. 5, 17v, 25v, 29v)</locus>
                        <note> Short Latin poems and proverbs</note>
                        <incipit><locus>(fol. 5)</locus> Tot video gentes</incipit>
                        <incipit><locus>(fol. 19v)</locus> Exiit edictum Augusto Caesare</incipit>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem>
                        <locus>(fols. 9v, 27v)</locus>
                        <note> 'De Joanne Potadwe' archbp. of Armenia, who came to England in 1228 with tidings of the Wandering Jew</note>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem>
                        <locus>(fol. 15)</locus>
                        <rubric>Problemata <persName key="person_35872894">Secundi philosophi</persName></rubric>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem>
                        <locus>(fol. 21)</locus>
                        <note> Latin note of a yearly indulgence at <orgName key="org_157729206">Eton</orgName></note>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem>
                        <locus>(fol. 22)</locus>
                        <author key="person_39768873">William of Nottingham</author>
                        <title key="work_5082">Commentary on Unum ex quattuor</title>
                        <note>(extracts)</note>
                        <rubric> Ex prologo Notyngham de concordia</rubric>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem>
                        <msItem>
                           <locus>(fol. 39)</locus>
                           <title key="work_14992">Computus ecclesiasticus manualis</title>
                           <incipit>Filius esto Dei</incipit>
                        </msItem>
                        <msItem>
                           <note>With prose commentary</note>
                        </msItem>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem class="#historica">
                        <locus>(fol. 51v)</locus>
                        <note> Latin note on the death of <persName key="person_64016139">King Richard I</persName></note>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem>
                        <locus>(fol. 53)</locus>
                        <author key="person_37012417">Donatus</author>
                        <title key="work_1425">Ars Minor</title>
                        <note>Here anonymous, cf. fol. 80v</note>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem>
                        <locus>(fol. 60v)</locus>
                        <author key="person_61943925">John of Bridlington (?)</author>
                        <title key="work_280">Versus prophetiales</title>
                        <rubric>Vaticinium Johannis Brydlyngtone </rubric>
                        <incipit>Febribus infectus</incipit>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem>
                        <locus>(fol. 66)</locus>
                        <title>Poem on chess</title>
                        <rubric>Ludus scaccorum</rubric>
                        <incipit>Si <sic>ic</sic> fit famosa sine sanguine pugna iocosa</incipit>
                        <bibl type="repertory"><ref target="http://webserver.erwin-rauner.de/php_ancarm/ancarm_refwerke.php?opus=1000&amp;var=WIC&amp;nr_char=8197"><title>WIC</title> 8197</ref></bibl>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem class="#astrologia_et_astronomia">
                        <locus>(fol. 69)</locus>
                        <note> 'Pronostica' astrologica</note>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem class="#topographica">
                        <locus>(fol. 73)</locus>
                        <note> 'The way to <placeName key="place_7000874">Rome</placeName> thorow <placeName key="place_1000070">France</placeName>', an itinerary</note>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem class="#computistica">
                        <note> (fols. 75, 87) Calendarial notes, in English</note>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem class="#scientifica">
                        <locus>(fol. 83)</locus>
                        <note> Tractatus de generatione hominis</note>
                        <incipit>Homo inter omnia animalia</incipit>
                        <bibl type="repertory"><ref target="https://cctr1.umkc.edu/find/$db=eTK&amp;ms=0636J">eTK 0636J</ref></bibl>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem class="#versus">
                        <locus>(fol. 87v)</locus>
                        <note> 'Colores versuum' or De modis xxx versificandi</note>
                        <note>Primus color quo moderni versiste vtuntur</note>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem>
                        <locus>(fol. 91)</locus>
                        <title key="work_15057" type="desc">Heraldic manual</title>
                        <rubric>Omnia vtilia ad arma pertinencia</rubric>
                        <incipit>Here begynth a scorth informacon of armis, how that</incipit>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem>
                        <locus>(fol. 95)</locus>
                        <title key="work_14784">Statuta universitatis Oxoniensis</title>
                        <note>A copy of some early statutes, including the Statuta Aularia (fol. 105)</note>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem>
                        <note><supplied>On <persName key="person_95890653">William Wykeham</persName></supplied></note>
                        <msItem>
                           <locus>(fol. 115)</locus>
                           <rubric>Testamentum ... domini Willelmi de Wykeham olim episcopi Wyntoniensis ...</rubric>
                        </msItem>
                        <msItem>
                           <note>Followed at fol. 121 by 'Cursus vite et actorum ... ' ejusdem, a short Latin biography</note>
                           <incipit>Natus est anno Domini 1334</incipit>
                        </msItem>
                        <msItem>
                           <note>Ending with statistics about <orgName key="org_150825867">Winchester</orgName> and <orgName key="org_130118418">New College</orgName> admissions 1394–1431, written in 1497</note>
                        </msItem>
                     </msItem>
                     <textLang mainLang="en" otherLangs="la">English and Latin</textLang>
                  </msItem>
